      <!-- Section 1: What Makes a Good AEO Study -->
      <section id="what-makes-a-good-aeo-study" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>What Makes a Good AEO Case Study?</h2>
        <p><strong>A credible AEO case study documents specific content and schema changes, measures defined AEO metrics before and after those changes, controls for concurrent SEO activity, and reports results over a time window long enough to isolate AEO impact from ranking noise.</strong></p>
        <p>Most published AEO case studies fail at least one of these criteria. The most common failure is conflating featured snippet acquisition with broader organic ranking improvements. If a site published forty new pages, gained significant backlinks, and also restructured its content for AEO in the same quarter, attributing snippet gains exclusively to AEO restructuring is methodologically indefensible.</p>
        <p>A rigorous study isolates variables. Ideally, it applies AEO changes to a defined set of pages while holding a control group constant, uses the same schema and structural changes across all treatment pages, and measures the same query set before and after. In practice, controlled experiments are difficult to run on live sites — but the closer a study gets to this standard, the more meaningful its conclusions.</p>
        <p>The discipline of <a href="/answer-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">answer engine optimisation</a> is part of the broader <a href="/generative-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">generative engine optimisation</a> framework — and like all of GEO, it is young enough that measurement standards are still being established. This page represents our current view of what good measurement looks like.</p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 2: Measurement Framework -->
      <section id="measurement-framework" class="anchor-top mb-16">
        <div class="prose-dark">
          <h2>The AEO Measurement Framework</h2>
          <p><strong>Measuring AEO performance requires five distinct metrics, each capturing a different answer-engine surface.</strong> Traditional SEO metrics — ranking position, organic traffic, click-through rate — are insufficient on their own because they do not track zero-click visibility, which is the primary value driver of AEO.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="mt-8 card overflow-hidden not-prose">
          <div class="overflow-x-auto">
            <table class="w-full text-left text-sm">
              <thead>
                <tr class="border-b border-[var(--line)]">
                  <th scope="col" class="px-5 py-4 font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--accent)]">Metric</th>
                  <th scope="col" class="px-5 py-4 font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--accent)]">What It Measures</th>
                  <th scope="col" class="px-5 py-4 font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--accent)]">Primary Tool</th>
                  <th scope="col" class="px-5 py-4 font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--accent)]">Min. Measurement Window</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
